/rest/api/2/issue/13042739/comment/15864815","id":"15864815","author":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=kabhwan","name":"kabhwan","key":"kabhwan","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Jungtaek Lim","active":true,"timeZone":"Asia/Seoul"},"body":"As I commented from https://github.com/apache/storm/pull/1919, below code comes from blog post on Confluent:\n\n{code}\ntry {\n  while (running) {\n  ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(1000);\n\n  try {\n    consumer.commitSync();\n    for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records)\n      System.out.println(record.offset() + \": \" + record.value());\n    } catch (CommitFailedException e) {\n      // application specific failure handling\n    }\n  }\n} finally {\n  consumer.close();\n}\n{code}\n\nwhich we can exactly do the same: poll the data, call commitSync(), and emit tuples only when commitSync() succeeds. It will guarantee at-most-once.","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=kabhwan","name":"kabhwan","key":"kabhwan","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Jungtaek Lim","active":true,"timeZone":"Asia/Seoul"},"created":"2017-02-14T01:16:13.225+0000","updated":"2017-02-14T01:16:13.225+0000"},{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/13042739/comment/15866858","id":"15866858","a